The National Institutes of Health report that obesity is the second-leading cause (after smoking) of preventable death in the United States today, and estimate that obesity-related disease costs the nation about $100 billion a year in direct health-care expenses or in lost productivity.
It said that the main reason for the rise is a rapid change in lifestyle and population demography, with growing obesity, Western-style diets, less physical exercise and a rising elderly population all contributing.
More than half of American citizens are overweight and one out of four is obese, according to the latest issue of Science.
